  "id": "global-cdn-performance-simulation",
  "name": "24-Hour Global CDN Traffic & Latency Simulation",
  "difficulty": "Performance Infrastructure",
  "description": "This visualization monitors global Content Delivery Network (CDN) health across five key regions. The data tracks request volume (primary Y-axis) and global average latency (secondary Y-axis) over a 24-hour cycle. <h3>Key Observations:</h3><ul><li><strong>Diurnal Patterns:</strong> Standard traffic follows regional daylight hours, with North America and Europe peaking between 16:00 and 20:00 UTC.</li><li><strong>The India 'Shock Event':</strong> At 14:00 UTC, a simulated 5x traffic spike occurs in the India region. Notice the corresponding surge in <strong>Global Avg Latency</strong>, which breaches the 200ms SLA threshold.</li><li><strong>Failover Recovery:</strong> Between 15:00 and 17:00, the system initiates 'Edge Scaling' and 'Traffic Rerouting'. You can observe traffic being offloaded to Southeast Asia and Australia nodes to stabilize the Indian origin, eventually bringing latency back within acceptable bounds.</li><li><strong>SLA Monitoring:</strong> Red markers and the secondary line indicate periods where packet loss and queue depth impacted user experience during peak utilization.</li></ul>",
  "tags": [
    "DevOps",
    "Edge Computing",
    "Traffic Engineering",
    "Reliability"
  ],
